qas.question: What is the American term Georgian restricted to?

context: <b5_0>Georgian architecture<b5_0/> is the name given in most English-speaking countries to the set of architectural styles current <a2_0>between 1714 and 1830<a2_0/>. It is eponymous for the first four British monarchs of the <a4_0>House of Hanover<a4_0/>—<a0_0>George I, George II, George III, and George IV<a0_0/>—who reigned in continuous succession from August 1714 to June 1830. The style was revived in the late 19th century in the United States as <a1_0><b6_0><b7_0>Colonial Revival<b6_0/><a1_0/> architecture<b7_0/> and in the early 20th century in Great Britain as <a3_0>Neo-Georgian<a3_0/> architecture; in both it is also called Georgian Revival architecture. In America the term "Georgian" is generally used to describe all building from the period, regardless of style; in Britain it is generally restricted to <b8_0>buildings that are "architectural in intention", and have stylistic characteristics that are typical of the period<b8_0/>, though that covers a wide range.
